"1631","1685":"1685","1683":"1683","about 1687":"circa 1687","27 November 1685":"27 november 1685","1727":"1727","Abbey, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Abbey, Renfrewshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Schotland","Abbey, Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Abbey, Renfrewshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Renfrew, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1653–about 1687":"1653–about 1687","1653–1687":"1653–1687","1657–Female":"1657–Deceased","1683–1727":"1683–1727","1685–Female":"1685–Deceased","1687–Male":"1687–Deceased","1631–Male":"1631–Deceased","1657":"1657","6 November 1683":"6 November 1683","1687":"1687","1653":"1653","14 February 1682":"14 February 1682","1631":"1631","1685":"1685","1683":"1683","about 1687":"about 1687","27 November 1685":"27 November 1685","1727":"1727","Abbey, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Abbey, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Abbey, Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Abbey, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Renfrew, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Finlayson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: from the Gaelic personal name <i>Fionnlagh</i> (see   Finley   1 and   Finlay  ) + <i>-son</i>. This is the Anglicized form of Scottish Gaelic <i>MacFhionnlaigh</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Fenlason","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Finlayson  ."]},{"name":"Fenderson","meanings":["Scottish: altered form of   Finlayson   or a variant of   Henderson  ."]},{"name":"Finlinson","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Finlayson  ."]},{"name":"Finley","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: from the Gaelic personal name <i>Fionnlagh</i> (Old Irish <i>Findlaech</i>), from <i>fionn</i> ‘white, fair’ (see   Finn  ) + <i>laoch</i> ‘hero’, reinforced by an Old Norse name based on <i>finn</i> ‘Finn’ + <i>leikr</i> ‘fight’ or ‘hero’. The name is common in Ireland as well as Scotland.","English: habitational name from one or more lost, unidentified or altered placenames so named, such as Philleyholme, Dorset (recorded as <i>Finelegh</i> in 1280) derived from Old English <i>fīna</i> ‘wood-pecker’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Also a variant of <b>Findlow</b>, from Finlow Hill in Over Alderley, Cheshire (from Old English <i>fīn</i> ‘heap’ + <i>hlāw</i> ‘mound, hill’ meaning ‘heaped mound’)."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"James Finlayson was born in 1653, in Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of james Finlayson. He married Margaret Wallace on 14 February 1682, in Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died about 1687, in Abbey, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1653–about 1687":"1653–umbes 1687","1653–1687":"1653–1687","1657–Female":"1657–Surnud","1683–1727":"1683–1727","1685–Female":"1685–Surnud","1687–Male":"1687–Surnud","1631–Male":"1631–Surnud","1657":"1657","6 November 1683":"6. november 1683","1687":"1687","1653":"1653","14 February 1682":"14. veebruar 1682","1631":"1631","1685":"1685","1683":"1683","about 1687":"umbes 1687","27 November 1685":"27. november 1685","1727":"1727","Abbey, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Abbey, Renfrewshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Abbey, Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Abbey, Renfrewshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Renfrew, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1653–about 1687":"1653–noin 1687","1653–1687":"1653–1687","1657–Female":"1657–Kuollut","1683–1727":"1683–1727","1685–Female":"1685–Kuollut","1687–Male":"1687–Kuollut","1631–Male":"1631–Kuollut","1657":"1657","6 November 1683":"6. marraskuuta 1683","1687":"1687","1653":"1653","14 February 1682":"14. helmikuuta 1682","1631":"1631","1685":"1685","1683":"1683","about 1687":"noin 1687","27 November 1685":"27. marraskuuta 1685","1727":"1727","Abbey, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Abbey, Renfrewshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Abbey, Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Abbey, Renfrewshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Renfrew, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt